Bee Colonies and Their Regional Stressors

Introduction¶

There's no denying the importance of honey bees as they are responsible for one-third of all crop production in the United States. Making sure crops such as melons, apples, cranberries, squash, pumpkins, broccoli, and almonds stay stocked in grocery stores. However in recent years the population of honey bees have rapidly decreasing, in 2012 there was an peak of 3.28 million colonies and today there are 2.88 million colonies. This decline is linked to multiple factors including climate change, pests, pesticides, and diseases.

For this project, I'll be examining datasets retrieved from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kyleahmurphy/nass-honey-bee-20152021, containing charts on bee colonies, bee stressors, and bee honey. The data was retrieved from reports within the beekeeping industry includes hobbyists, part-timers, and commercial beekeepers. According to agmrc.org:

"Hobby-sized operations are those with 25 colonies or less, hobbyists with less than 5 colonies are not included in the colonies reported by the USDA. Part-timers are those with 25 to 300 colonies, and commercial operations are those with over 300 colonies. Hobbyists and part-timers account for roughly 40 percent of the honey production, and 1,600 commercial beekeepers are responsible for the remaining 60 percent of production."
This project aims to examine the leading stressors that lead to bee colony losses in different regions in the U.S.

Since the goal is to identify the the most influential stressors on bee colonies, it is necessary to first identify if the bee colonies are experiencing a noticable loss in their colony populations. I chose to use the percent loss column since its more standardized compared to the lost colonies column, since each colonies are different sizes the number of lost colonies may differ in magnitude.

Now that the bee colony data is more readable, taking a look at the means of each region's mean percent loss over the years shows that the Southwest region has the highest average percent loss of bee colonies of 13%. The region with the least average percent loss is the Northeast region at 9%.

Based on the graphs it seems that there's a correlation between the season of the year and average percent loss. To further examine a possible relationship, the data corresponding to the spring and summer months as well as the fall and winter months must be grouped for each region.

One thing to note is that honey bees operate in seasons. Warmer seasons, like spring and summer are when bees fly out and forage, collecting resources such as nectar to feed their brood (baby bees). The majority of the brood then grow into more workers that collect more resources for the colony. During the fall the bees prepare to overwinter, basically waiting out winter, and collect resources as well as kick out the drone bees to prepare for it.

On the violin plots the light blue portion plotted shows the distribution of each states' percent losses within a specific region. Bee Colony Renovation Data Exploration¶

Renovation includes requeening a surviving colony, which may help in increasing a colony's brood production, or a large transfer of honey bees into a colony either by nuc or package. A nucleus colony, also known as a split or a nuc, is typically a pre-established hive frame containing a queen, bees, honey, brood, and pollen. While a package only has bees and a queen. Both types are usually installed during the spring and they are helpful in boosting a weak colony's resources in the long run.

A nucleus colony: Package of bees:

For this dataset I want to see if there's a correlation between the percent loss and percent renovated other than yearly upkeep.

Bee Stressor Dataset Exploration¶

Bee infected with varroa mites and deformed wing virus

In addition to their winter survival, imported bee species face a variety of different stressors. Including pesticides, pests such as hive beetles and varroa mites, environmental stress, diseases, and even a phenomenon called colony collapse disorder. This section aims to identify the major stressors for bee colonies from each U.S. region from 2015-2021.

Looking at the graph and summary statistics, all of the regions have varroa mites as their primary stressor over a period of 6 years. Ranging from 10% to 49% over all regions. With the Southern regions having the highest average percentage of varroa mites of 32%. Interestingly enough the varroa mites percentage in the Southwest, Midwest, and South have increased their winter seasons presence each year from 2015-2018. In all the regions except for the South region, the presence of mites reached a new minimum during the winter of 2018 or 2019. Another interesting insight is that the South region has higher pests/parasites percentages than any other U.S. region.

Now lets see if there's a correlation between the varroa mites and colony loss. If there is a correlation, we would expect to see that the periods of times where the varroa mites population is higher, the percentage in colony loss is higher as well.

Surpisingly not all regions have varroa mites strongly correlated to their percent losses! Hypothesis Testing¶

To test some hypotheses, the statsmodels libraries needs to be imported to use the linear regression model. The model can vertify if there's a moderate relationship between a region and certain stressors. The datasets also need to be prepped for the model such that all the states/dates in the dataset has an associated percentage for a certain stressor as well as a percent loss in colonies.

# Performing linear regression on the West region dataset
# Set x to be all the stressors and y to be percent loss
x = w_final[['Varroa Mites (Percent)','Other pests and parasites (Percent)', 'Diseases (percent)', 'Pesticides (percent)', 'Other (percent)', 'Unknown (percent)']]

# Get the linear regression model's intercept and coefficients
regr = linear_model.LinearRegression()
regr.fit(x, y)

print('Intercept: \n', regr.intercept_)
print('Coefficients: \n', regr.coef_)

# Fit linear regression model
x = sm.add_constant(x)
model = sm.OLS(y, x).fit()
predictions = model.predict(x)

Conclusion¶

From the hypothesis testing, the most significant findings were that the Northeast region had a moderate correlation between its percent loss and varroa mites, other factors, and some unknown factors. While the Southwest region saw a moderate correlation between its percent loss and varroa mites. Other regions had a weak relationships with some stressors. Such as the West region having a small percentage of percent loss affected by pesticides, Midwest having a small percentage of percent loss affected by other factors, and the South having a small percentage of percent loss affected by other and unknown factors. For the most part, the regression reflected the correlations that were noticed during the data exploration.

It would be worth investigating what stressors make up the "Other" factors in the future, whether it could be related to climate change or abnormal bee colony behavior. But the main course of action would be figuring out how to deal with varroa mite populations.
